<p align='center'><font color='#000080' face='Arial'><strong>HASTE ITEMS AND SPELLS, JANUARY 8, 2000</strong></font></p>

<hr size='1' width='85%'>

<div align='center'><center>


<table border='0' width='85%'>
  <tr>
    <td valign='top' align='left'><font face='Arial' size='2'><b>Introduction</b></font><p><font
    face='Arial' size='2'>One of the most important aspects of Everquest is obviously melee.
    Without someone in there smashing, slashing, piercing, stabbing and crushing the enemy, it
    is surely going to be an ugly day&#146;s gaming. As characters develop and mature the key
    question becomes, how does one deal the maximum damage in the quickest possible time? Now
    whilst this game is meant to have role-playing elements, we have to accept that for the
    vast majority of players, getting experience is the name of the game. In this article I
    hope to show how to maximize the use of Haste bonuses to improve your killing ability. I
    will be focusing on Level 50 characters, but the principles discussed will be relevant to
    lower level characters as well.&nbsp; Hopefully when you have finished reading this
    article you will see that in many circumstances the Shaman haste buffs, and some of the
    lower level enchanter haste buffs are actually as effective, or moreso, than their level
    49 counterpart.</font></p>
    <b><p><font face='Arial' size='2'>The Ground Rules</font></b></p>
    <p><font face='Arial' size='2'>Killing quickly and efficiently has a number of benefits.
    Firstly, it means you can increase your overall kills per hour. More kills, less downtime
    means more levels. Pure and simple. Secondly, the faster you kill a monster means less
    damage taken to you in many instances. Unless you have a permanent stun caster around to
    keep things from attacking, monsters will be hitting you while you are hitting them. The
    faster they fall, the less bleeding you will do. Thirdly, if you take too long killing an
    enemy you take a greater risk of more enemies coming along to join in. Basically, there
    are definite advantages to killing faster. So how do you go about doing it? In Everquest
    there are two methods: Haste items, and Haste spells.</font></p>
    <p><font face='Arial' size='2'>There are some basic ground rules for dealing with haste
    which were put forward by Gordon Wrinn of Verant in January 2000. These are as follows:</font><ol>
      <li><font face='Arial' size='2'>Haste items can stack with haste-spells. </font></li>
      <li><font face='Arial' size='2'>Haste items do have different speeds. As a rule, its speed
        will basically be based off the level creature that it came from. </font></li>
      <li><font face='Arial' size='2'>Haste items do not stack with other haste-items. </font></li>
      <li><font face='Arial' size='2'>Haste spells do not stack with other haste spells. </font></li>
    </ol>
    <b><p><font face='Arial' size='2'>Maximizing Haste</font></b></p>
    <p><font face='Arial' size='2'>So how do you maximize the effectiveness of your attacks as
    a melee, and as a buffing caster, how do you use the right spells to do the best job? This
    comes down to first of all speaking to the group you are in before you get going. There
    are two questions you need to ask.</font><ol>
      <li><font face='Arial' size='2'>What weapons does everyone have?</font></li>
      <li><font face='Arial' size='2'>Does anyone have haste items, if so what ones?</font></li>
    </ol>
    <p><font face='Arial' size='2'>Whilst there is no cap on how fast any given class can
    attack, there is a cap on how much your attack speed can be increased with the use of
    haste-items and spells.&nbsp; As such there is an indirect cap on maximum attack rate
    dependent on your weapon.&nbsp; As a player, be you melee or otherwise, you need to get a
    good idea of what your items do, and what buffs maximize your effectiveness in a group.
    Before I give some specific examples, lets look at the three&nbsp;classes with speed
    buffs. Enchanters, Shamans, and Bards.</font></p>
    <p><font face='Arial' size='2'>Let&#146;s take the Enchanter first. The Enchanter has two
    main haste-type series available <strong>Quicken</strong> Spells, and also the <strong>Augmentation
    </strong>spell.</font></p>
    <p><font face='Arial' size='2'>Quicken spells are comprised of <strong>Quickness</strong>
    (Level 16), <strong>Alacrity</strong> (Level 24), <strong>Celerity</strong> (Level 39), <strong>Swift
    Like the Wind</strong> (Level 49). These spells are pure haste increasing spells. The
    advantage to using them is that they provide at high levels the fastest haste bonuses in
    the game.&nbsp; The downside is they chew both a lot of mana and run out fairly quickly.
    Their duration&#146;s range from 3 to 10 minutes.&nbsp; One thing to note however, Swift
    Like the Wind will take any class to its maximum attack rate, so it should generally only
    be used when there are no other haste benefits on the target.</font></p>
    <p><font face='Arial' size='2'>On the other hand we have <strong>Augmentation</strong>
    (Level 29), which besides giving a speed boost, also gives an Agility and AC boost, and
    Stamina Regeneration. This is one of the best buffs available for any melee. Other
    advantages are that the spell lasts 27 minutes, and uses very little mana. The problem is
    that the speed boost is only around that of Alacrity at Level 50. </font></p>
    <p><font face='Arial' size='2'>Shamans only get two speed spells. <strong>Quickness </strong>at
    Level 29 and<strong> Alacrity </strong>at Level 44. They operate exactly the same as the
    Enchanter spells.</font></p>
    <p><font face='Arial' size='2'>Bards have a number of songs which give haste. &nbsp;
    However, both Shaman and Enchanter haste spells will override the haste component of the
    songs.&nbsp; If you only have a Bard around then use the <strong>Level 50</strong> or <strong>Level
    42</strong> songs.&nbsp; You can also twist <strong>Level 1</strong> and <strong>Level 50</strong>,
    or <strong>Level 1</strong>, <strong>Level 50</strong> and <strong>Level 32 </strong>if
    you want some mana song in there.&nbsp; For the rest of this editorial though we will
    focus on Enchanters and Shamans, and the use of their haste spells.</font></p>
    <p><font face='Arial' size='2'>Also, the Enchanter werewolf illusion form has a built in
    haste component. This haste component is the same as the method used with the Monk class,
    and is completely stackable with both haste items and spells.&nbsp; This can be especially
    useful if using high damage, high delay weapons.</font></p>
    <p><font face='Arial' size='2'><b>Making the Choices</b></font></p>
    <p><font face='Arial' size='2'>So how do you decide which to use? I will give a few
    examples:</font></p>
    <b><p><u><font face='Arial' size='2'>Monks</font></u></b></p>
    <p><font face='Arial' size='2'>The monk class has a built in haste-effect in their class.
    This is completely stackable with both haste items, and haste spells. Consider three
    different monks. Monk A has a flowing black silk sash, Monk B has a cloak of flames, and
    Monk C has no haste items at all. They are in a group with a Shaman and Enchanter, which
    spells should they use on who?</font></p>
    <p><font face='Arial' size='2'>Monk A should consider a tough choice between Celerity, and
    Augmentation. Since Monks have lower AC than tanks, the extra AC and Agility off
    Augmentation will be worthwhile. However, Monks have the highest haste cap, meaning they
    can be accelerated more than any other class in the game. With the FBSS you can stack
    Celerity and get the maximum attacks per round (Celerity is used over Swift Like the Wind
    (SLTW) because it uses half the mana, and provides the same effect with a FBSS). If you
    use Augmentation you will get less overall haste once stacked with the FBSS than with
    celerity (because the max haste cap is so high on Monks). So the choice is dependent
    really upon who is in the group. If you have some high taunters in the group you can
    probably use Celerity as they will help to keep the Monk from getting a beat down. If on
    the other hand the Monk is doing partial tanking, you are probably better off going for
    Augmentation for it&#146;s other benefits. With Shamans, Alacrity is the spell of choice.</font></p>
    <p><font face='Arial' size='2'>Monk B should definitely stick with Augmentation. The Cloak
    of Flames has a better haste effect than the FBSS, and once stacked with Alacrity will put
    the Monk very close to the maximum haste bonus. Using Augmentation on the Monk will give
    them the same speed as if Alacrity had been used, plus the extra benefits of the spell.
    This also frees the Enchanter to use the Berserker Spirit spell on the Monk without
    reducing their base agility. This will mean higher damage from the Strength increase, as
    well as a very nice protective skin. Shaman&#146;s would once again use Alacrity amongst
    their normal buffs of Strength and the like. This would be the same advice for a Monk with
    the Haste Gauntlets or Cloak from the Plane of Hate. </font></p>
    <p><font face='Arial' size='2'>Monk C, having no haste items, should definitely request
    Swift Like the Wind (SLTW). This will put the monk at its maximum haste cap. Using
    Augmentation on a Monk with no haste items would only be useful in places such as Kedge
    Keep, where keeping stamina up is more difficult from the swimming required. Shaman&#146;s
    would once again use Alacrity.</font></p>
    <b><p><u><font face='Arial' size='2'>Weapon Melee&#146;ers</font></u></b></p>
    <p><font face='Arial' size='2'>I have grouped all the weapon Melee&#146;ers together to
    save on repetition. There are a number of weapon&#146;s in Norrath which have haste
    effects. The most renowned are the Executioners Axe, and the Mithril Two-Handed Sword. The
    first thing, and perhaps most important to note, is that these items don't all stack the
    same way.&nbsp; </font></p>
    <p><font face='Arial' size='2'>The haste effect from the Mithril 2 Hander <u>does not
    stack</u> with any other haste-item. So if you have a FBSS or Cloak of Flames, then the
    haste effect on this weapon is totally useless. Make a choice at this point: go for
    different armor, or a different weapon. Nice alternatives to consider are the Thick Banded
    Belt, the Razing Sword of Skarlon, Dual Ykesha&#146;s, or any of the Dragon or Plane
    Weapons.&nbsp; </font></p>
    <p><font face='Arial' size='2'>On the other hand weapons such as the Executioner Axe and
    Ashenwood Short Spear cast a haste spell.&nbsp; This works like a proc, and these weapons <u>do
    not stack</u> with Shaman, Enchanter or Bard haste spells, even though the spell is cast
    off an item.&nbsp; In this case you are better off putting the item away and using the PC
    spell or song, as the haste procs only last for very short durations and are normally
    overridden by the PC cast spell anyway (with the exception of low-level PC haste spells).
    &nbsp; </font></p>
    <p><font face='Arial' size='2'>By Level 50 most Rogues will generally will have a FBSS,
    and won&#146;t have the problem with haste-weapons since there aren&#146;t any daggers
    with haste (although Drelzna&#146;s spear has limited charges). They can replace the FBSS
    with another belt item if they are lucky enough to get loot off Nagafen.</font></p>
    <p><font face='Arial' size='2'>That being said, it can pay off to carry a variety of
    weapons around with you. If you aren&#146;t grouped with a buffer, and don&#146;t have
    haste armor, then pull out your haste weapon. If you do get a buffer put the haste weapon
    away and pull out a slower one with a bigger damage. With a level 50 Enchanter weapon
    based melee'ers can always hit at max speed, with a Shaman you can only do so if you have
    haste armor.</font></p>
