    <p><font face='Arial' size='2'>The above chart illustrates how for weapons with a lower
    attack delay, you can combine the lower level Augmentation spell and still achieve very
    close to the max attack rate.&nbsp; Without the haste item you would probably need to use
    a higher level spell.&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; </font></p>
    <p><font face='Arial' size='2'>It also shows clearly for weapons with higher delays, you
    will only be able to use the lower level spells if you have a high level haste item, such
    as one off a dragon or from the planes.&nbsp; The more ordinary haste items like the FBSS
    or Swirlspine Belts will not be enough to max your haste cap with Augmentation with these
    weapons.&nbsp; However, the attack rate isn't always that much of a difference, and in
    many circumstances, the extra agility, AC, and stamina regen will be helpful.&nbsp; Do not
    underestimate the stamina regen component of the Enchanters Augmentation spell.&nbsp; When
    you are swinging at your max rate, you will drop stamina relatively quickly, and if you
    can use the lower level buff then this won't be a problem.&nbsp; Also swinging a high
    damage-slow weapon faster is generally more useful than swinging a lower damage-high speed
    weapon even faster.</font></p>
    <p><font face='Arial' size='2'>You also need to keep in mind that dual wielding is made
    substantially more powerful by haste effects, effectively halving the net attack delay if
    you have two separate weapons of the same speed.&nbsp; You can also note though, that in
    some circumstances, with the right buffs and equipment, you could wield two normally quite
    slow weapons, with high damage and still attack at your maximum attack speed.</font></p>
