    </center></div><p><font face='Arial' size='2'><b>Conclusion</b></font></p>
    <p><font face='Arial' size='2'>In summary then, it is not just the buffers responsibility
    to make sure a melee is receiving the right spell. It is both up to the melee&#146;er and
    the buffer to work together. The melee&#146;er has to carry an assortment of equipment to
    allow the buffer to maximize their damage potential. Ideally the melee&#146;er should
    carry one high damage, but slower delay weapon. A couple of dual wielding weapons of
    medium damage, medium delay, and one haste weapon. They should also make it a priority to
    get an FBSS. Since items like the Cloak of Flames, Bolster Belts and the like are much
    rarer (being Dragon loot, or from the Planes) not everyone will have one, but any serious
    high level melee'er should take the time to go and acquire a sash. </font></p>
    <p><font face='Arial' size='2'>At the end of the day if you have a haste item and a haste
    buffer you should <u>always</u> be able to fight at your maximum attack rate. The real
    trick is to find the best weapon to do it with to get the highest damage per round. Even
    ultra slow high damage weapons like Mroon&#146;s Toy can become devastatingly effective if
    combined with the right items and spells.</font></p>
    <p><font face='Arial' size='2'>Maximizing your haste is, as with most things in Everquest,
    a grouped effort, but one that can make an enormous difference to your daily life in
    combat. Take the time to experiment with different combinations of weapons, haste-items
    and buffs, and learn what works best for your character.</font></p>
